    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mt-4">Project 1: SMB File Share via Windows In-Built Tools</h1>

    <section class="mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Networking</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
        <li>Created the shared folder in Windows so other computers can see it on the network.</li>
        <li>Allowed access only from trusted IP address ranges (e.g., computers on our office network).</li>
        <li>Disabled any “allow everyone” network rules so unknown devices can’t reach the share.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Security</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
        <li>Set folder access permissions so only specific people or groups can open, change, or save files.</li>
        <li>Matched the folder’s Windows security (NTFS) permissions with the share permissions.</li>
        <li>Turned off old, unsafe SMB version (SMBv1) that hackers could exploit.</li>
        <li>Kept the newer, safer SMB versions (SMBv2 and SMBv3) running for compatibility.</li>
        <li>Tested setup:
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-6 mt-2 space-y-1">
            <li>Trusted computer can connect normally.</li>
            <li>Untrusted computer is blocked.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">What This Means</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-slate-700">
        Only trusted devices inside the office network can access the shared folder. People outside of that network, or without permission, can’t even see the share. The connection uses a newer, safer version of file sharing.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
